<hr />

<p>The limericks directory contains five-line narratives about incidents that would otherwise be unbearable, mascot biographies written in the meter of bad decisions, and rhyme-schemed summaries of doctrine drift and metrics theatre.</p>

<p>They function as <strong>unauthorized executive summaries</strong>: too flippant for dashboards, too specific to be dismissed.</p>

<p>Use limericks when you want to see how a governance pattern feels from the bottom of the form, to recognize a recurring failure by its punchline, or to triangulate an incident you half-remember by the fact it once scanned.</p>

<p>They are not policy. They are the jokes the archive tells about itself when it thinks COMA isn't listening.</p>

<p>If a case file feels heavy, there is probably a limerick version of it here. Read at your own risk; some punchlines are binding.</p>

